\subsubsection{Traffic issue detection model}
For traffic issue, \app~uses 3Sigma and Pearson correlation coefficient for anomaly detection.
As shown in Figure \ref{fig:qps-time}, QPS is more in line with the characteristics of normal distribution, 3Sigam represents that 99.73\% of the data is distributed in the range of negative 3Sigma to positive 3Sigma, these data are considered to fluctuate within the normal range, and the data beyond this range are considered abnormal.

In this paper, we take the QPS one hour before the alarm occurs on the edge as the detection data, and calculate the mean and variance with the data of the previous 50 minutes, then use 3Sigma to perform anomaly detection based on the last 10 minutes data.
If a value of QPS is not within the 3Sigma interval of the last 10 minutes, we think this service may have traffic issue.
However, we observed that 3Sigma is still prone to false positives, therefore, we calculate the correlation score between QPS of the current node and the metrics that triggers the alarm based on Pearson correlation coefficient.
Only when the score is higher then a certain threshold(e.g., 0.9), it will be finally confirmed that there is a traffic issue exists in this service.

\begin{figure}[ht]
	\centering
	\includegraphics[width=0.45\textwidth]{images/qps-time.png}
	\vspace{-8pt}
	\caption{Change of QPS Over Time}\label{fig:qps-time}
	\vspace{-10pt}
\end{figure}


